From
\href{Science:Math_Exam_Resources/Courses/MATH307/April_2013/Question_Section_202_06_(a)}{part
(a)} the coefficients of the Fourier series were found to be:

\begin{align*}
c_0 &= \frac{1}{2}  \\
c_n &= \begin{cases}
0 & \text{if } n \text{ is even, } n \not= 0 \\ 
\frac{-i}{\pi n} & \text{if } n \text{ is odd}
\end{cases} \end{align*}

This
yields\begin{align*}f(x)= c_0+\sum_{n \text{ odd, } n=-\infty}^{\infty} \frac{-i}{\pi n} e^{2\pi inx}\end{align*}

Parseval$^{\prime}$s Theorem states:

\begin{align*}\int_{a}^{b}\left | f(x) \right |^2=\sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}\left | c_n \right |^2\end{align*}

Computing the left side:

\begin{align*}\mathrm{LHS} = \int_{a}^{b}\left | f(x) \right |^2=\int_{0}^{1/2}1^2=\frac{1}{2}\end{align*}

Computing the right side:

\begin{align*}\mathrm{RHS} = \sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}\left | c_n \right |^2=(\frac{1}{2})^2+\sum_{n \text{ odd, } n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{\pi ^2n^2}+\sum_{n \text{ odd, } n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{\pi ^2(-n)^2}\end{align*}

Here the sum of odds from $-\infty$ to $\infty$ was split into two sums
from 1 to $\infty$ and -1 to $-\infty$. It can be observed that the
second sum is the same as the first where $n=-n$ and since $(-n)^2=n^2$,
these two sums are equivalent.

\begin{align*}\mathrm{RHS} = (\frac{1}{2})^2+2(\sum_{n \text{ odd, } n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{\pi ^2n^2})\end{align*}

To get the expression that we want we can make a substitution of
variables to remove the odd restriction in our sum. Let $n=2k+1$. It can
be seen that for \emph{k=0,1,2,3,...}, \emph{n} will always be odd.

Note: Making this substitution will change summation range.

At $n=1, 1=2k+1 \Rightarrow k=0$. So the new summation range will be
$k=0$ to $\infty$.

\begin{align*}\mathrm{RHS} =\frac{1}{4}+2(\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{\pi ^2(2k+1)^2})\end{align*}

Using the left side that was computed above we get:

\begin{align*}\frac{1}{2}=\frac{1}{4}+\frac{2}{\pi ^2}(\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{(2k+1)^2})\end{align*}

Rearranging this to get the final answer:

\begin{align*}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{(2k+1)^2}=\frac{\pi ^2}{8}\end{align*}
